         <abstract>
            <p>This paper demonstrates that a mathematical bias can result if historical data are used to calculate beta coefficients after a company's "true" beta has undergone a change. At times, an increase in a company's riskiness can actually lower its calculated beta coefficient, and if the calculated beta is used to appraise a firm's risk, the analysis can be misleading. Included is a discussion of the problems that this may present for electric and telephone utilities.</p>
         </abstract>
